# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: wazuh-monitoring
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:wazuh-monitoring/endpoint-security] The endpoint security space has evolved during the 2010s away from limited antivirus software and into a more advanced, comprehensive defense.
[src:wazuh-monitoring/endpoint-security] This includes next-generation antivirus, threat detection, investigation, and response, device management, data leak protection (DLP), and other considerations to face evolving threats.
[src:wazuh-monitoring/endpoint-security] Endpoint security management is a software approach that helps to identify and manage the users' computer and data access over a corporate network.
[src:wazuh-monitoring/endpoint-security] This allows the network administrator to restrict the use of sensitive data as well as certain website access to specific users, to maintain, and comply with the organization's policies and standards.
[src:wazuh-monitoring/endpoint-security] The components involved in aligning the endpoint security management systems include a virtual private network (VPN) client, an operating system and an updated endpoint agent.
[src:wazuh-monitoring/endpoint-security] Computer devices that are not in compliance with the organization's policy are provisioned with limited access to a virtual LAN.
[src:wazuh-monitoring/endpoint-security] Encrypting data on endpoints, and removable storage devices help to protect against data leaks.
[src:wazuh-monitoring/endpoint-security] Endpoint security systems operate on a client-server model, with the security program controlled by a centrally managed host server pinned with a client program that is installed on all the network drives.
[src:wazuh-monitoring/endpoint-security] There is another model called software as a service (SaaS), where the security programs and the host server are maintained remotely by the merchant.
[src:wazuh-monitoring/endpoint-security] In the payment card industry, the contribution from both the delivery models is that the server program verifies and authenticates the user login credentials and performs a device scan to check if it complies with designated corporate security standards prior to permitting network access.
[src:wazuh-monitoring/endpoint-security] In addition to protecting an organization's endpoints from potential threats, endpoint security allows IT admins to monitor operation functions and data backup strategies.
[src:wazuh-monitoring/endpoint-security] An endpoint protection platform (EPP) is a solution deployed on endpoint devices to prevent file-based malware attacks, detect malicious activity, and provide the investigation and remediation capabilities needed to respond to dynamic security incidents and alerts.
[src:wazuh-monitoring/endpoint-security] Several vendors, like Microsoft Defender, CrowdStrike, and Absolute Security, produce systems converging EPP systems with endpoint detection and response (EDR) platforms – systems focused on threat detection, response, and unified monitoring.
[src:wazuh-monitoring/file-integrity-monitoring] Generally, the act of performing file integrity monitoring is automated using internal controls such as an application or process.
[src:wazuh-monitoring/file-integrity-monitoring] Such monitoring can be performed randomly, at a defined polling interval, or in real-time.
[src:wazuh-monitoring/file-integrity-monitoring] Changes to configurations, files and file attributes across the IT infrastructure are common, but hidden within a large volume of daily changes can be the few that impact file or configuration integrity.
[src:wazuh-monitoring/file-integrity-monitoring] These changes can also reduce security posture and in some cases may be leading indicators of a breach in progress.
[src:wazuh-monitoring/file-integrity-monitoring] Multiple compliance objectives indicate file integrity monitoring as a requirement.
[src:wazuh-monitoring/host-based-intrusion-detection-system] HIDS focuses on more granular and internal attacks through focusing monitoring host activities instead of overall network traffic.
[src:wazuh-monitoring/host-based-intrusion-detection-system] HIDS was the first type of intrusion detection software to have been designed, with the original target system being the mainframe computer where outside interaction was infrequent.
[src:wazuh-monitoring/host-based-intrusion-detection-system] One major issue with using HIDS is that it needs to be installed on each and every computer that needs protection from intrusions.
[src:wazuh-monitoring/host-based-intrusion-detection-system] This can lead to a slowdown in device performance and intrusion detection systems.
[src:wazuh-monitoring/host-based-intrusion-detection-system] A host-based IDS is capable of monitoring all or parts of the dynamic behavior and the state of a computer system, based on how it is configured.
[src:wazuh-monitoring/host-based-intrusion-detection-system] Similarly a HIDS might look at the state of a system, its stored information, whether in RAM, in the file system, log files or elsewhere; and check that the contents of these appear as expected, e.g. have not been changed by intruders.
[src:wazuh-monitoring/host-based-intrusion-detection-system] One can think of a HIDS as an agent that monitors whether anything or anyone, whether internal or external, has circumvented the system's security policy.
[src:wazuh-monitoring/host-based-intrusion-detection-system] In comparison to network-based intrusion detection systems, HIDS is advantageous because of its capability of identifying internal attacks.
[src:wazuh-monitoring/host-based-intrusion-detection-system] While NIDS examines data from network traffic, HIDS examines data originating from operating systems.
[src:wazuh-monitoring/host-based-intrusion-detection-system] In recent years, HIDS has been faced with the big data challenge, which can be attributed to the increased advancement of data center facilities and methodologies.
[src:wazuh-monitoring/host-based-intrusion-detection-system] Many computer users have encountered tools that monitor dynamic system behavior in the form of anti-virus (AV) packages.
[src:wazuh-monitoring/host-based-intrusion-detection-system] While AV programs often also monitor system state, they do spend a lot of their time looking at who is doing what inside a computer – and whether a given program should or should not have access to particular system resources.
[src:wazuh-monitoring/host-based-intrusion-detection-system] The lines become blurred here, as many of the tools overlap in functionality.
[src:wazuh-monitoring/host-based-intrusion-detection-system] Some intrusion prevention systems protect against buffer overflow attacks on system memory and can enforce security policy.
[src:wazuh-monitoring/host-based-intrusion-detection-system] The principle operation of a HIDS depends on the fact that successful intruders (hackers) will generally leave a trace of their activities.
[src:wazuh-monitoring/host-based-intrusion-detection-system] In theory, a computer user has the ability to detect any such modifications, and the HIDS attempts to do just that and reports its findings.
[src:wazuh-monitoring/host-based-intrusion-detection-system] Ideally a HIDS works in conjunction with a NIDS, such that a HIDS finds anything that slips past the NIDS.
[src:wazuh-monitoring/host-based-intrusion-detection-system] Commercially available software solutions often do correlate the findings from NIDS and HIDS in order to find out about whether a network intruder has been successful or not at the targeted host.
[src:wazuh-monitoring/host-based-intrusion-detection-system] Most successful intruders, on entering a target machine, immediately apply best-practice security techniques to secure the system which they have infiltrated, leaving only their own backdoor open, so that other intruders can not take over *their* computers.
[src:wazuh-monitoring/host-based-intrusion-detection-system] In general a HIDS uses a database (object-database) of system objects it should monitor – usually (but not necessarily) file system objects.
[src:wazuh-monitoring/host-based-intrusion-detection-system] A HIDS could also check that appropriate regions of memory have not been modified – for example, the system call table for Linux, and various vtable structures in Microsoft Windows.
[src:wazuh-monitoring/host-based-intrusion-detection-system] For each object in question a HIDS will usually remember its attributes (permissions, size, modifications dates) and create a checksum of some kind (an MD5, SHA1 hash or similar) for the contents, if any.
[src:wazuh-monitoring/host-based-intrusion-detection-system] This information gets stored in a secure database for later comparison (checksum database).
[src:wazuh-monitoring/host-based-intrusion-detection-system] An alternate method to HIDS would be to provide NIDS type functionality at the network interface (NIC) level of an end-point (either server, workstation or other end device).
[src:wazuh-monitoring/host-based-intrusion-detection-system] Providing HIDS at the network layer has the advantage of providing more detailed logging of the source (IP address) of the attack and attack details, such as packet data, neither of which a dynamic behavioral monitoring approach could see.
[src:wazuh-monitoring/host-based-intrusion-detection-system] At installation time – and whenever any of the monitored objects change legitimately – a HIDS must initialize its checksum-database by scanning the relevant objects.
[src:wazuh-monitoring/host-based-intrusion-detection-system] Persons in charge of computer security need to control this process tightly in order to prevent intruders making un-authorized changes to the database(s).
[src:wazuh-monitoring/host-based-intrusion-detection-system] Such initialization thus generally takes a long time and involves cryptographically locking each monitored object and the checksum databases or worse.
[src:wazuh-monitoring/host-based-intrusion-detection-system] Because of this, manufacturers of HIDS usually construct the object-database in such a way that makes frequent updates to the checksum database unnecessary.
[src:wazuh-monitoring/host-based-intrusion-detection-system] Computer systems generally have many dynamic (frequently changing) objects which intruders want to modify – and which a HIDS thus should monitor – but their dynamic nature makes them unsuitable for the checksum technique.
[src:wazuh-monitoring/host-based-intrusion-detection-system] To overcome this problem, HIDS employ various other detection techniques: monitoring changing file-attributes, log-files that decreased in size since last checked, and numerous other means to detect unusual events.
[src:wazuh-monitoring/host-based-intrusion-detection-system] Reports can take the form of logs, e-mails or similar.
[src:wazuh-monitoring/host-based-intrusion-detection-system] A HIDS will usually go to great lengths to prevent the object-database, checksum-database and its reports from any form of tampering.
[src:wazuh-monitoring/host-based-intrusion-detection-system] After all, if intruders succeed in modifying any of the objects the HIDS monitors, nothing can stop such intruders from modifying the HIDS itself – unless security administrators take appropriate precautions.
[src:wazuh-monitoring/host-based-intrusion-detection-system] Many worms and viruses will try to disable anti-virus tools, for example.
[src:wazuh-monitoring/host-based-intrusion-detection-system] Apart from crypto-techniques, HIDS might allow administrators to store the databases on a CD-ROM or on other read-only memory devices (another factor in favor of infrequent updates...) or storing them in some off-system memory.
[src:wazuh-monitoring/host-based-intrusion-detection-system] Similarly, a HIDS will often send its logs off-system immediately – typically using VPN channels to some central management system.
[src:wazuh-monitoring/host-based-intrusion-detection-system] One could argue that the trusted platform module comprises a type of HIDS.
[src:wazuh-monitoring/host-based-intrusion-detection-system] Although its scope differs in many ways from that of a HIDS, fundamentally it provides a means to identify whether anything/anyone has tampered with a portion of a computer.
[src:wazuh-monitoring/host-based-intrusion-detection-system] Architecturally this provides the ultimate (at least at this point in time) host-based intrusion detection, as depends on hardware external to the CPU itself, thus making it that much harder for an intruder to corrupt its object and checksum databases.
[src:wazuh-monitoring/host-based-intrusion-detection-system] InfoWorld states that host-based intrusion-detection system software is a useful way for network managers to find malware, and suggest they run it on every server, not just critical servers.
[src:wazuh-monitoring/log-management] The primary drivers for log management implementations are concerns about security, system and network operations (such as system or network administration) and regulatory compliance.
[src:wazuh-monitoring/log-management] Logs are generated by nearly every computing device, and can often be directed to different locations both on a local file system or remote system.
[src:wazuh-monitoring/log-management] Users and potential users of log management may purchase complete commercial tools or build their own log-management and intelligence tools, assembling the functionality from various open-source components, or acquire (sub-)systems from commercial vendors.
[src:wazuh-monitoring/log-management] Log management is a complicated process and organizations often make mistakes while approaching it.
[src:wazuh-monitoring/log-management] Logging can produce technical information usable for the maintenance of applications or websites.
[src:wazuh-monitoring/log-management] Organizations can use different log-analyzers for analyzing the logs of devices in the security perimeter, typically aiming to identify patterns of attack on the perimeter infrastructure of the organization.
[src:wazuh-monitoring/log-management] Organizations may mandate logging to identify the access and usage of confidential data within the security perimeter.
[src:wazuh-monitoring/log-management] A log analyzer can also track and monitor the performance and availability of systems at the level of the enterprise, especially of those information assets whose availability organizations regard as vital.
[src:wazuh-monitoring/log-management] Organizations may integrate the logs of various business applications into an enterprise log manager for a better value proposition.
[src:wazuh-monitoring/ossec] In June 2008, the OSSEC project and all the copyrights owned by Daniel B.
[src:wazuh-monitoring/ossec] Cid, the project leader, were acquired by Third Brigade, Inc.
[src:wazuh-monitoring/ossec] They promised to continue to contribute to the open source community and to extend commercial support and training to the OSSEC open source community.
[src:wazuh-monitoring/ossec] In May 2009, Trend Micro acquired Third Brigade and the OSSEC project, with promises to keep it open source and free.
[src:wazuh-monitoring/ossec] In 2018, Trend released the domain name and source code to the OSSEC Foundation.
[src:wazuh-monitoring/ossec] The OSSEC project is being developed and maintained by Atomicorp who stewards the free and open source version and also offers a commercial version.
[src:wazuh-monitoring/ossec] OSSEC consists of a main application, an agent, and a web interface.
[src:wazuh-monitoring/syslog] In computing, **syslog** (/ˈsɪslɒɡ/) is a standard for message logging.
[src:wazuh-monitoring/syslog] It allows separation of the software that generates messages, the system that stores them, and the software that reports and analyzes them.
[src:wazuh-monitoring/syslog] Each message is labeled with a facility code, indicating the type of system generating the message, and is assigned a severity level.
[src:wazuh-monitoring/syslog] Computer system designers may use syslog for system management and security auditing as well as general informational, analysis, and debugging messages.
[src:wazuh-monitoring/syslog] A wide variety of devices, such as printers, routers, and message receivers across many platforms, use the syslog standard.
[src:wazuh-monitoring/syslog] This permits the consolidation of logging data from different types of systems in a central repository.
[src:wazuh-monitoring/syslog] Implementations of syslog exist for many operating systems.
[src:wazuh-monitoring/syslog] When operating over a network, syslog uses a client-server architecture where a **syslog server** listens for and logs messages coming from clients.
[src:wazuh-monitoring/syslog] Syslog was developed in the 1980s by Eric Allman as part of the Sendmail project.
[src:wazuh-monitoring/syslog] It was readily adopted by other applications and has since become the standard logging solution on Unix-like systems.
[src:wazuh-monitoring/syslog] A variety of implementations also exist on other operating systems and it is commonly found in network devices, such as routers.
[src:wazuh-monitoring/syslog] Syslog originally functioned as a de facto standard, without any authoritative published specification, and many implementations existed, some of which were incompatible.
[src:wazuh-monitoring/syslog] The Internet Engineering Task Force documented the status quo in RFC 3164 in August 2001.
[src:wazuh-monitoring/syslog] It was standardized by RFC 5424 in March 2009.
[src:wazuh-monitoring/syslog] Various companies have attempted to claim patents for specific aspects of syslog implementations.
[src:wazuh-monitoring/syslog] This has had little effect on the use and standardization of the protocol.
[src:wazuh-monitoring/syslog] The information provided by the originator of a syslog message includes the facility code and the severity level.
[src:wazuh-monitoring/syslog] The syslog software adds information to the information header before passing the entry to the syslog receiver.
[src:wazuh-monitoring/syslog] Such components include an originator process ID, a timestamp, and the hostname or IP address of the device.
[src:wazuh-monitoring/syslog] A facility code is used to specify the type of system that is logging the message.
[src:wazuh-monitoring/syslog] Messages with different facilities may be handled differently.
[src:wazuh-monitoring/syslog] The mapping between facility code and keyword is not uniform in different operating systems and syslog implementations.
[src:wazuh-monitoring/syslog] The meaning of severity levels other than *Emergency* and *Debug* are relative to the application.
[src:wazuh-monitoring/syslog] For example, if the purpose of the system is to process transactions to update customer account balance information, an error in the final step should be assigned *Alert* level.
[src:wazuh-monitoring/syslog] However, an error occurring in an attempt to display the ZIP code of the customer may be assigned *Error* or even *Warning* level.
[src:wazuh-monitoring/syslog] The server process that handles display of messages usually includes all lower (more severe) levels when the display of less severe levels is requested.
[src:wazuh-monitoring/syslog] That is, if messages are separated by individual severity, a *Warning* level entry will also be included when filtering for *Notice*, *Info* and *Debug* messages.
[src:wazuh-monitoring/syslog] In RFC 3164, the message component (known as MSG) was specified as having these fields: *TAG*, which should be the name of the program or process that generated the message, and *CONTENT* which contains the details of the message.
[src:wazuh-monitoring/syslog] Described in RFC 5424, "MSG is what was called CONTENT in RFC 3164.
[src:wazuh-monitoring/syslog] The TAG is now part of the header, but not as a single field.
[src:wazuh-monitoring/syslog] The TAG has been split into APP-NAME, PROCID, and MSGID.
[src:wazuh-monitoring/syslog] This does not totally resemble the usage of TAG, but provides the same functionality for most of the cases." Popular syslog tools such as NXLog, Rsyslog conform to this new standard.
[src:wazuh-monitoring/syslog] The content field should be encoded in a UTF-8 character set and octet values in the traditional ASCII control character range should be avoided.
[src:wazuh-monitoring/syslog] Generated log messages may be directed to various destinations, including: console, files, remote syslog servers, or relays.
[src:wazuh-monitoring/syslog] Most implementations provide a command line utility, often called *logger*, as well as a software library, to send messages to the log.
[src:wazuh-monitoring/syslog] To display and monitor the collected logs, one needs to use a client application or access the log file directly on the system.
[src:wazuh-monitoring/syslog] The basic command line tools are tail and grep.
[src:wazuh-monitoring/syslog] The log servers can be configured to send the logs over the network (in addition to the local files).
[src:wazuh-monitoring/syslog] Some implementations include reporting programs for filtering and displaying syslog messages.
[src:wazuh-monitoring/syslog] When operating over a network, syslog uses a client-server architecture where the server listens on a well-known or registered port for protocol requests from clients.
[src:wazuh-monitoring/syslog] Historically the most common transport layer protocol for network logging has been User Datagram Protocol (UDP), with the server listening on port 514.
[src:wazuh-monitoring/syslog] Because UDP lacks congestion control mechanisms, Transmission Control Protocol (TCP) port 6514 is used; Transport Layer Security is also required in implementations and recommended for general use.
[src:wazuh-monitoring/syslog] Since each process, application, and operating system was written independently, there is little uniformity to the payload of the log message.
[src:wazuh-monitoring/syslog] For this reason, no assumption is made about its formatting or contents.
[src:wazuh-monitoring/syslog] A syslog message is formatted (RFC 5424 gives the Augmented Backus–Naur form (ABNF) definition), but its MSG field is not.
[src:wazuh-monitoring/syslog] The network protocol is simplex communication, with no means of acknowledging the delivery to the originator.
[src:wazuh-monitoring/syslog] Various groups are working on draft standards detailing the use of syslog for more than just network and security event logging, such as its proposed application within the healthcare environment.
[src:wazuh-monitoring/syslog] Regulations, such as the Sarbanes–Oxley Act, PCI DSS, HIPAA, and many others, require organizations to implement comprehensive security measures, which often include collecting and analyzing logs from many different sources.
[src:wazuh-monitoring/syslog] The syslog format has proven effective in consolidating logs, as there are many open-source and proprietary tools for reporting and analysis of these logs.
[src:wazuh-monitoring/syslog] Utilities exist for conversion from Windows Event Log and other log formats to syslog.
[src:wazuh-monitoring/syslog] Managed Security Service Providers attempt to apply analytical techniques and artificial intelligence algorithms to detect patterns and alert customers to problems.
[src:wazuh-monitoring/syslog] The Syslog protocol is defined by Request for Comments (RFC) documents published by the Internet Engineering Task Force (Internet standards).
